      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bill McKibben (Op-Ed, Sept. 4) is right to wonder what will shock us into waking up to the realities of global warming. However, our actions are determined as much by the incentive systems shaped by our economic and social institutions as by individual perceptions.</p>
        <p>Many Americans are aware of the coming environmental crisis but are personally unwilling to do anything about it until they see everyone else doing something as well. Once we appreciate this societal nature of the problem, it is easier to recognize that our inaction results more from a lack of collective political leadership than from individual disinterest or neglect.</p>
        <p>FRANK FISCHER  Newark, Sept. 7, 1999</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of political science at Rutgers University.</p>
      </block>
